04835nam a22006015i 9780822388616DE-B159720201125033335.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201125t20062006ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223886167 a10.1515/97808223886162doi  a(DE-B1597)553782  a(OCoLC)1224278157  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aE185.615b.Y58 2006 7aHIS0360002bisacsh1 aYoung, Cynthia A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSoul Power :bCulture, Radicalism, and the Making of a U.S. Third World Left /cCynthia A. Young. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2006] 4cÂ©2006  a1 online resource (328 p.) :b10 b&w photos  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 ae-Duke books scholarly collection00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Havana Up in Harlem and Down in Monroe -- t2. Union Power, Soul Power -- t3. Newsreel -- t4. Third World Newsreel Visualizes the Internal Colony -- t5. Angela Y. Davis and U.S. Third World Left Theory and Praxis -- t6. Shot in Watts -- tCoda -- tNotes -- tBibliography and Filmography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSoul Power is a cultural history of those whom Cynthia A. Young calls "U.S. Third World Leftists," activists of color who appropriated theories and strategies from Third World anticolonial struggles in their fight for social and economic justice in the United States during the "long 1960s." Nearly thirty countries in Africa, Asia, and Latin America declared formal independence in the 1960s alone. Arguing that the significance of this wave of decolonization to U.S. activists has been vastly underestimated, Young describes how literature, films, ideologies, and political movements that originated in the Third World were absorbed by U.S. activists of color. She shows how these transnational influences were then used to forge alliances, create new vocabularies and aesthetic forms, and describe race, class, and gender oppression in the United States in compelling terms.Young analyzes a range of U.S. figures and organizations, examining how each deployed Third World discourse toward various cultural and political ends. She considers a trip that LeRoi Jones, Harold Cruse, and Robert F. Williams made to Cuba in 1960; traces key intellectual influences on Angela Y. Davis's writing; and reveals the early history of the hospital workers' 1199 union as a model of U.S. Third World activism. She investigates Newsreel, a late 1960s activist documentary film movement, and its successor, Third World Newsreel, which produced a seminal 1972 film on the Attica prison rebellion. She also considers the L.A. Rebellion, a group of African and African American artists who made films about conditions in the Watts neighborhood of Los Angeles. By demonstrating the breadth, vitality, and legacy of the work of U.S. Third World Leftists, Soul Power firmly establishes their crucial place in the history of twentieth-century American struggles for social change.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aAfrican American political activistsxHistoryy20th century. 0aAfrican AmericansxIntellectual lifey20th century. 0aAfrican AmericansxPolitics and governmenty20th century. 0aAnti-imperialist movementszDeveloping countriesxHistoryy20th century. 0aMinoritiesxPolitical activityzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aRadicalismzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aSocial justicezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822388616zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps:/